a coordinating-only node that can handle transform APIs without needing security enabled. For the transform to actually work and advance checkpoints, I need to think through which approach gives me a node that can properly execute transforms within the cluster.\n\nActually, maybe I'm overcomplicating this. The es-transform pod doesn't necessarily need to be a full cluster member—it could just be a way to represent transform capacity while the actual transform jobs run on the existing 3-node cluster. Let me reconsider what the configuration would look like for a proper transform-dedicated node in ES 7.17, since the syntax differs between versions.\n\nThe pragmatic path forward is to mount the same TLS certificates on the es-transform StatefulSet that the main nodes use, create a transform-specific config similar to the existing one, and then scale it up. This would let the es-transform node properly join the cluster and provide actual transform capacity. I need to check which TLS secret handles the transport layer encryption. I'm reconsidering whether es-transform actually needs to join the main cluster or if it's just a separate tool that manages transforms via the API. Either way, since it's using the Elasticsearch image, I'll take the practical approach: patch the StatefulSet to mount the certs volume, create a ConfigMap with the proper SSL configuration for the transform node, then scale it up and create the transform job through the HTTPS API.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2735,"cache_read_input_tokens":45205,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":2735},"output_tokens":35,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"7de1427c-cc3f-491a-bf74-e6942814c17c","uuid":"93691b3f-1eef-4ede-b49d-9af05a688978","request_id":"req_011Cc8v7E